title: Trump’s Relentless Self-Promotion Fosters an American Cult of Personality
partialText: President Trump has engaged in a spree of self-aggrandizement unlike any of his predecessors, fostering a mythologized superhuman persona and making himself the inescapable force at home and around the world.

title: Like Trump, U.S. Embassies Are Raising Cash for Lavish July Fourth Parties
partialText: Some of Washington’s diplomatic outposts in Asia are raising millions for events to mark the 250th independence anniversary. One ambassador offered to sing and dance.

title: Canada Gives U.S. Arms Makers the Cold Shoulder on Military Spending
partialText: Canada plans to unveil a new strategy that will shift its current reliance on American companies to Canadian military suppliers.

title: Trump Administration Ends Credit for Start-Stop Feature in Cars
partialText: Manufacturers will no longer get a credit toward vehicle emissions standards by installing engines that automatically stop at red lights.

title: Three American Speeches at Munich, and Plenty of Confusion
partialText: As the U.S. message veered from shared heritage and values to shared interests and back again, Europeans wondered what kind of alliance they were left with.

title: In Munich, Lawmakers Concede Scars Remain After Trump’s Greenland Threat
partialText: Congress members said that President Trump’s coveting of Greenland had left a mark, even as they expressed hope for a less bellicose approach to foreign relations.

title: Trump’s Stinging Attack on Israel’s President Touches a Nerve
partialText: President Trump called President Isaac Herzog of Israel “disgraceful” because he has not yet pardoned Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in his corruption trial.

title: Republican State Legislators Rush to Limit Their Own Regulators
partialText: South Carolina’s state legislature is one of 17, mainly in heavily Republican states, that is moving to handcuff state agencies at a moment of tectonic changes in energy, technology and finance.

title: What to Know About the Homeland Security Shutdown
partialText: Funding for the Department of Homeland Security lapsed on Saturday amid a standoff over restrictions that Democrats have demanded for federal immigration agents. But much of its work continues.

title: Winter Storms Could Bring 8 Feet of Snow to Parts of California
partialText: The greatest impact is expected across Northern California, where a pair of powerful storms are expected to begin on Sunday night and last into the week.

title: Light Snowfall Coming to New York, New Jersey and Long Island
partialText: Forecasters said snowfall totals of one to two inches were likely Sunday night, with isolated amounts of up to three inches across New York City, northeastern New Jersey and much of Long Island.

title: Diplomatic Feud With China Weighs on Japan’s Economy
partialText: A standoff over the security of Taiwan has led to a steep decline in the number of Chinese visitors to Japan, which is heavily dependent on the tourists.

title: How A.I. Salaries Are Causing Couples to Rethink Money in Relationships
partialText: The artificial intelligence frenzy is creating personal fortunes rarely seen in modern technology and changing people’s attitudes about fairness and money in relationships.

title: Tax Missteps Happen — Even When Two Financial Pros are Married
partialText: You’d think a financial planner married to another financial planner would have it easy come tax time. Alas, no.

title: Warner Bros. Is Said to Consider Reopening Talks With Paramount
partialText: Warner Bros. Discovery had agreed to sell itself to Netflix, but its contract allows it to pursue offers that may lead to a superior deal.

title: In the East Village, Hiding in Plain Sight: A Secret Passage to the Underground Railroad
partialText: A passageway hidden below a dresser at the Merchant’s House Museum had long been a mystery. Then researchers learned that the home’s original builder was an abolitionist.

title: On the Las Vegas Strip, Local Acts at Delilah and Elsewhere Set the Vibe
partialText: On the Strip and beyond, clubs, bars and restaurants spotlight local performers who deliver some of the city’s best entertainment.

title: What C.E.O.s Are Worried About
partialText: Fractured politics, disruptive technologies and a distrust in institutions are making it harder to focus on the traditional tasks of growing sales and profits.

title: How $40-a-Pack Cigarettes Pushed Australians to the Black Market
partialText: Tax hikes made cigarettes in Australia the most expensive in the world. They have also helped fuel a multibillion-dollar criminal enterprise in bootleg tobacco.

title: Gisèle Pelicot, the Woman at the Center of Rape Trial That Shook France, Shares Her Story
partialText: In her first interview with an American media outlet, Pelicot opens up about surviving years of secret abuse — and a trial that shocked the world.

title: ‘A Hymn to Life’ Review: Gisèle Pelicot’s Memoir Is a Powerfully Written Feminist Manifesto
partialText: With matter-of-fact precision, “A Hymn to Life” powerfully chronicles the shock of discovering her husband’s sex crimes, and the rallying cry that followed.

title: Ro Khanna Is Shaken by What He’s Learned From the Epstein Files
partialText: Epstein’s network may not have known everything, but it is hard to deny that many of them knew enough to know better.

title: The War in Ukraine Has Become a Way of Life
partialText: The war in Ukraine can look like the future and the past at once. But it’s just our present, the only one we know.

title: Bans on Many CBD Products Loom This Year
partialText: A federal law taking effect in November severely limits the amount of THC, the euphoric cannabis compound, allowed in over-the-counter items. Many groups are fighting back.

title: ‘Wuthering Heights’ Gallops Toward $82 Million in Global Ticket Sales
partialText: Warner Bros. spent an estimated $80 million on the R-rated romance, directed by Emerald Fennell, not including hefty marketing costs.

title: In First Public Comments Since Trump’s Racist Video, Obama Laments Lost Decorum
partialText: In a podcast interview, former President Barack Obama did not directly address the video posted by Mr. Trump but denounced a “clown show” on social media.
